Executive Summary

This report summarizes production performance across PetroTech Energy's 120 well portfolio spanning the
Alpha, Bravo, and Charlie fields. The portfolio produced 49,952 bbl/day of oil and 49,793 Mscf/day of gas at
an average water cut of 30.6% and average reservoir pressure of 2,402 psi. Of the 120 wells, 114 are active
and 6 are shut-in, while 20 wells (16.7% of the portfolio) meet the intervention criteria of water cut above 50%
or downtime exceeding 25 hours. Electrical Submersible Pumps (ESP) are the clear top performer, averaging
559 bbl/day per well versus 396 bbl/day for Gas Lift and 224 bbl/day for Rod Pump a pattern confirmed by
the fact that all ten highest-producing wells run ESP, while eight of the ten lowest producing wells run Rod
Pump.

Production Overview

Alpha field leads the portfolio with 19,121 bbl/day of oil across 44 wells, supported by the highest average
reservoir pressure (2,472 psi) and the lowest average water cut (28.7%) of the three fields. Charlie field ranks
second at 15,612 bbl/day (39 wells), while Bravo field contributes the least oil at 15,219 bbl/day despite
operating 37 wells and carrying the highest average water cut of any field (33.7%). The gap between Alpha
and Bravo is consistent with a reservoir quality effect rather than a well count effect, since Alpha and Charlie
have a similar well count but a materially different water cut.

Operational Issues

● Water cut: Portfolio average is 30.6%, but Bravo field runs highest at 33.7%, and 20 wells individually
exceed the 50% threshold, indicating advancing water breakthrough in specific zones rather than a
field wide issue.
● Pressure decline: Underperforming wells cluster in the 800–1,400 psi range, well below the 2,402 psi
portfolio average, suggesting localized reservoir depletion or inadequate artificial lift support.
● Downtime: Average downtime is 17.3 hours per well, but several wells  concentrated on Rod Pump
completions report downtime as high as 90 hours, pointing to reliability issues with that lift method.
● Pump performance gap: Rod Pump wells combine the lowest average oil rate (224 bbl/day) with the
highest average water cut (33.6%) of any pump type, making them the weakest-performing asset class in
the portfolio.

Recommendations

1 Prioritize workover and intervention on the 20 flagged wells (water cut >50% or downtime >25 hrs),
beginning with Charlie field, where most low-producing wells cluster.
2 Evaluate converting underperforming Rod Pump wells to ESP or Gas Lift where reservoir pressure can
support the change, given the 2.5x production differential between ESP and Rod Pump wells.
3 Investigate water breakthrough in Bravo field through conformance treatment or selective water shutoff,
targeting its above average 33.7% water cut.
4 Implement predictive maintenance scheduling for Rod Pump wells specifically, to reduce the portfolio's
17.3 hour average downtime and prevent runs to 90+ hours.
5 Direct near term development capital toward Alpha field style completions, which combine the highest
reservoir pressure and lowest water cut in the portfolio.

Expected Benefits

Executing these recommendations is expected to increase portfolio oil production by reducing losses from the
20 flagged wells, lower average downtime below the current 17.3 hour baseline, reduce operating cost per
barrel by addressing Rod Pump reliability issues, and improve overall field efficiency by aligning artificial lift
selection with reservoir pressure conditions across Alpha, Bravo, and Charlie fields.
